# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cellular-6g
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] ITU-R oversees related work by 3GPP and ETSI, together with the Next Generation Mobile Networks (NGMN) Alliance.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] 3GPP is finalizing Release 18 for 5G Advanced and preparing Release 19 for early 6G research.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] IMT-2030 defines performance targets for future mobile systems and tracks 6G standardization.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Research and testing are in progress at major equipment vendors, operators, and institutes.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Companies including Ericsson, Nokia, Huawei, Samsung, LG, Apple, NTT Docomo, Airtel, and Jio have announced 6G programs.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Governments in North America, Europe, and Asia are funding national 6G initiatives through the EU, the United States, Russia, China, India, Japan, and South Korea.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] 6G aims to achieve higher data rates, lower latency, and greater energy efficiency than 5G.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Planned advances include new air interface designs, improved coding and modulation, and reconfigurable intelligent surfaces.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Research also explores integration with satellite, Wi-Fi, and non-terrestrial networks, as well as distributed edge computing for AR, VR, and AI applications.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Machine learning and AI are expected to help manage networks, allocate spectrum, and optimize services.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] According to the NGMN Alliance, 6G development should focus on demonstrable user needs and avoid unnecessary replacement of existing 5G radio access network equipment.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Analysts note that 5G revenue growth has been slower than predicted, leading to a cautious approach to 6G investment.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Commercial deployment of 6G is anticipated in the early 2030s, following standardization milestones later in the 2020s.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] 6G networks are expected to be developed and released by the early 2030s.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] The largest number of 6G patents have been filed in China.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Academic publications since the early 2020s have been conceptualizing 6G and new features that may be included.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] The frequency bands for 6G are undetermined.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] One of the challenges in supporting the required high transmission speeds will be the limitation of energy consumption and associated thermal protection in the electronic circuits.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] As of now, mid bands are being considered by WRC for 6G/IMT-2030.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] In June 2021, according to Samsung's white paper, using Sub-THz 6G spectrum, their indoor data rate was successful for 6 Gbit/s at 15 meters distance.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] The following year, Samsung reported 12 Gbit/s at 30 meters distance and 2.3 Gbit/s at 120 meters distance.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] In September 2023, LG successfully tested 6 Gbit/s transmission and reception at 500 meters distance outdoor.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Research into terahertz radiation (300–3,000 GHz) and millimeter-wave frequencies (30–300 GHz) explores their potential for 6G mobile networks.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] These high frequencies can support large data rates but are easily blocked by obstacles.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Unlike the microwave bands (2–30 GHz) used in 5G and Wi-Fi, and the lower-frequency radio waves used in 1G–4G, their commercial feasibility remains uncertain, as 5G millimeter-wave use is limited by cost.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] In 2020, the Alliance for Telecommunications Industry Solutions (ATIS) launched the Next G Alliance, a group including AT&T, Ericsson, Telus, Verizon, T-Mobile, Microsoft, and Samsung.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] The alliance aims to advance North American 6G research.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] In 2022, researchers from Purple Mountain Laboratories, a state-affiliated institute in Nanjing, China, reported a 206.25 Gbit/s data rate in laboratory tests using the terahertz band.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] The team said the results may support future 6G research.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Also in 2022, another Chinese research group reported a data transmission rate of 1 Tbit/s over 1 km using vortex millimeter-wave transmission, a technique that uses radio waves shaped to spiral as they travel.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] The work built on earlier European studies from the 1990s.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Vortex waves weaken as they expand with distance.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] The researchers used a custom transmitter and receiver to focus and decode multiple rotating wave modes.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] In 2023, Nagoya University in Japan created three-dimensional waveguide structures made of superconducting niobium for communication in the 100 GHz range.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] The superconducting design reduced signal loss from absorption and radiation and was proposed for high-frequency 6G transmission.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Research on terahertz and millimeter-wave communication continues worldwide as part of global efforts to develop future wireless standards.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] In November 2020, China launched a Long March 6 vehicle that carried a satellite testing components for potential 6G communication.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Chinese state media described it as "the world's first 6G satellite", a claim not independently verified.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] The mission studied terahertz-band transmission and other 6G-related technologies.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Geopolitical competition during the rollout of 5G has continued to shape the development of 6G.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] During that time, China reduced participation by foreign vendors and relied more on domestic suppliers such as Huawei and ZTE.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Several Western countries later restricted Huawei and ZTE after government investigations accused Chinese firms of cyber-espionage and intellectual-property theft.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] These developments affected early 6G planning and global supply chains.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Analysts have suggested that such divisions could lead to a split in 6G standards.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Analysts also expect competition in international standards bodies to grow.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] A joint statement issued in February 2024 by the United States, Australia, Canada, Czech Republic, Finland, France, Japan, South Korea, Sweden, and the United Kingdom endorsed shared 6G principles for open, global, and secure connectivity.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Governments in several countries, including China and India, have made 6G a national priority.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] The technology appears in China's Fourteenth Five-Year Plan.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] India's 6G direction is defined by the Bharat 6G Vision document, published in 2023.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Governments have also promoted varied technology suppliers.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Many support the Open RAN model, which lets hardware and software from different suppliers work together without vendor control.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] Australia's telecommunications strategy includes early 6G planning.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] In March 2025, Telstra announced that 6G is expected in the 2030s, with $800 million set aside to improve existing infrastructure over four years.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] 6G wireless communication networks are envisioned to revolutionize customer services and applications via the IoT (Internet of Things) toward a future of fully intelligent and autonomous systems.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] IoT connects sensor devices and networks to enable communication among people, physical objects, and equipment across a wide range of contexts.
[src:cellular-6g/6g-network] 6G will also use Backscatter Communication for Ambient IoT devices.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Beamforming can be used for radio or sound waves.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] It has found numerous applications in radar, sonar, seismology, wireless communications, radio astronomy, acoustics and biomedicine.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Adaptive beamforming is used to detect and estimate the signal of interest at the output of a sensor array by means of optimal (e.g., least-squares) spatial filtering and interference rejection.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] To change the directionality of the array when transmitting, a beamformer controls the phase and relative amplitude of the signal at each transmitter, in order to create a pattern of constructive and destructive interference in the wavefront.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] When receiving, information from different sensors is combined in a way where the expected pattern of radiation is preferentially observed.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] The beamforming technique involves sending the pulse from each projector at slightly different times (the projector closest to the ship last), so that every pulse hits the ship at exactly the same time, producing the effect of a single strong pulse from a single powerful projector.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] The same technique can be carried out in air using loudspeakers, or in radar/radio using antennas.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Receive beamforming can also be used with microphones or radar antennas.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] With narrowband systems the time delay is equivalent to a "phase shift", so in this case the array of antennas, each one shifted a slightly different amount, is called a phased array.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] A narrow band system, typical of radars, is one where the bandwidth is only a small fraction of the center frequency.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] With wideband systems this approximation no longer holds, which is typical in sonars.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] In the receive beamformer the signal from each antenna may be amplified by a different "weight." Different weighting patterns (e.g., Dolph–Chebyshev) can be used to achieve the desired sensitivity patterns.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] A main lobe is produced together with nulls and sidelobes.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] As well as controlling the main lobe width (beamwidth) and the sidelobe levels, the position of a null can be controlled.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] This is useful to ignore noise or jammers in one particular direction, while listening for events in other directions.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] A similar result can be obtained on transmission.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] For the full mathematics on directing beams using amplitude and phase shifts, see the mathematical section in phased array.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Conventional beamformers, such as the Butler matrix, use a fixed set of weightings and time-delays (or phasings) to combine the signals from the sensors in the array, primarily using only information about the location of the sensors in space and the wave directions of interest.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] In contrast, adaptive beamforming techniques (e.g., MUSIC, SAMV) generally combine this information with properties of the signals actually received by the array, typically to improve rejection of unwanted signals from other directions.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] This process may be carried out in either the time or the frequency domain.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] As the name indicates, an adaptive beamformer is able to automatically adapt its response to different situations.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Some criterion has to be set up to allow the adaptation to proceed such as minimizing the total noise output.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Because of the variation of noise with frequency, in wide band systems it may be desirable to carry out the process in the frequency domain.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Beamforming can be computationally intensive.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Sonar phased array has a data rate low enough that it can be processed in real time in software, which is flexible enough to transmit or receive in several directions at once.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] In contrast, radar phased array has a data rate so high that it usually requires dedicated hardware processing, which is hard-wired to transmit or receive in only one direction at a time.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] However, newer field programmable gate arrays are fast enough to handle radar data in real time, and can be quickly re-programmed like software, blurring the hardware/software distinction.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Sonar beamforming utilizes a similar technique to electromagnetic beamforming, but varies considerably in implementation details.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Sonar applications vary from 1 Hz to as high as 2 MHz, and array elements may be few and large, or number in the hundreds yet very small.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] This will shift sonar beamforming design efforts significantly between demands of such system components as the "front end" (transducers, pre-amplifiers and digitizers) and the actual beamformer computational hardware downstream.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] High frequency, focused beam, multi-element imaging-search sonars and acoustic cameras often implement fifth-order spatial processing that places strains equivalent to Aegis radar demands on the processors.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Many sonar systems, such as on torpedoes, are made up of arrays of up to 100 elements that must accomplish beam steering over a 100 degree field of view and work in both active and passive modes.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Sonar arrays are used both actively and passively in 1-, 2-, and 3-dimensional arrays.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Sonar differs from radar in that in some applications such as wide-area-search all directions often need to be listened to, and in some applications broadcast to, simultaneously.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] In a narrowband sonar receiver, the phases for each beam can be manipulated entirely by signal processing software, as compared to present radar systems that use hardware to 'listen' in a single direction at a time.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Sonar also uses beamforming to compensate for the significant problem of the slower propagation speed of sound as compared to that of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] In side-look-sonars, the speed of the towing system or vehicle carrying the sonar is moving at sufficient speed to move the sonar out of the field of the returning sound "ping".
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] In addition to focusing algorithms intended to improve reception, many side scan sonars also employ beam steering to look forward and backward to "catch" incoming pulses that would have been missed by a single sidelooking beam.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] The delay-and-sum beamforming technique uses multiple microphones to localize sound sources.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] One disadvantage of this technique is that adjustments of the position or of the number of microphones changes the performance of the beamformer nonlinearly.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Additionally, due to the number of combinations possible, it is computationally hard to find the best configuration.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] One of the techniques to solve this problem is the use of genetic algorithms.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Such algorithm searches for the microphone array configuration that provides the highest signal-to-noise ratio for each steered orientation.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Experiments showed that such algorithm could find the best configuration of a constrained search space comprising ~33 million solutions in a matter of seconds instead of days.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Beamforming techniques used in cellular phone standards have advanced through the generations to make use of more complex systems to achieve higher density cells, with higher throughput.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] An increasing number of consumer 802.11ac Wi-Fi devices with MIMO capability can support beamforming to boost data communication rates.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] To receive (but not transmit), there is a distinction between analog and digital beamforming.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] For example, if there are 100 sensor elements, the "digital beamforming" approach entails that each of the 100 signals passes through an analog-to-digital converter to create 100 digital data streams.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Then these data streams are added up digitally, with appropriate scale-factors or phase-shifts, to get the composite signals.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] By contrast, the "analog beamforming" approach entails taking the 100 analog signals, scaling or phase-shifting them using analog methods, summing them, and then usually digitizing the *single* output data stream.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Digital beamforming has the advantage that the digital data streams (100 in this example) can be manipulated and combined in many possible ways in parallel, to get many different output signals in parallel.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] The signals from every direction can be measured simultaneously, and the signals can be integrated for a longer time when studying far-off objects and simultaneously integrated for a shorter time to study fast-moving close objects, and so on.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] This cannot be done as effectively for analog beamforming, not only because each parallel signal combination requires its own circuitry, but more fundamentally because digital data can be copied perfectly but analog data cannot.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] (There is only so much analog power available, and amplification adds noise.) Therefore, if the received analog signal is split up and sent into a large number of different signal combination circuits, it can reduce the signal-to-noise ratio of each.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] In MIMO communication systems with large number of antennas, so called massive MIMO systems, the beamforming algorithms executed at the digital baseband can get very complex.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] In addition, if all beamforming is done at baseband, each antenna needs its own RF feed.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] At high frequencies and with large number of antenna elements, this can be very costly, and increase loss and complexity in the system.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] To remedy these issues, hybrid beamforming has been suggested where some of the beamforming is done using analog components and not digital.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] There are many possible different functions that can be performed using analog components instead of at the digital baseband.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Beamforming, whether done digitally, or by means of analog architecture, has recently been applied in Integrated Sensing and Communication (ISAC), also known as Joint Communication and Sensing (JCAS), technology.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] For instance, a beamformer was suggested, in imperfect channel state information situations to perform communication tasks, while at the same time performing target detection to sense targets in the scene.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Beamforming can be used to try to extract sound sources in a room, such as multiple speakers in the cocktail party problem.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] This requires the locations of the speakers to be known in advance, for example by using the time of arrival from the sources to mics in the array, and inferring the locations from the distances.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Compared to carrier-wave telecommunications, natural audio contains a variety of frequencies.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] It is advantageous to separate frequency bands prior to beamforming because different frequencies have different optimal beamform filters (and hence can be treated as separate problems, in parallel, and then recombined afterward).
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Properly isolating these bands involves specialized non-standard filter banks.
[src:cellular-6g/beamforming] Instead, filters can be designed in which only local frequencies are detected by each channel (while retaining the recombination property to be able to reconstruct the original signal), and these are typically non-orthogonal unlike the FFT basis.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] A **cellular network** or **mobile network** is a telecommunications network where the link to and from end nodes is wireless and the network is distributed over land areas called ***cells***, each served by at least one fixed-location transceiver (such as a base station).
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] These base stations provide the cell with the network coverage which can be used for transmission of voice, data, and other types of content via radio waves.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Each cell's coverage area is determined by factors such as the power of the transceiver, the terrain, and the frequency band being used.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] A cell typically uses a different set of frequencies from neighboring cells, to avoid interference and provide guaranteed service quality within each cell.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] When joined, these cells provide radio coverage over a wide geographic area.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The design of cellular networks allows for seamless handover, enabling uninterrupted communication when a device moves from one cell to another.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Modern cellular networks utilize advanced technologies such as Multiple Input Multiple Output (MIMO), beamforming, and small cells to enhance network capacity and efficiency.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Major telecommunications providers have deployed voice and data cellular networks over most of the inhabited land area of Earth.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] This allows mobile phones and other devices to be connected to the public switched telephone network and public Internet access.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In addition to traditional voice and data services, cellular networks now support internet of things (IoT) applications, connecting devices such as smart meters, vehicles, and industrial sensors.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The evolution of cellular networks from 1G to 5G has progressively introduced faster speeds, lower latency, and support for a larger number of devices, enabling advanced applications in fields such as healthcare, transportation, and smart cities.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In a cellular radio system, a land area to be supplied with radio service is divided into cells in a pattern dependent on terrain and reception characteristics.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] These cell patterns roughly take the form of regular shapes, such as hexagons, squares, or circles although hexagonal cells are conventional.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Each of these cells is assigned with multiple frequencies (*f*1 – *f*6) which have corresponding radio base stations.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The group of frequencies can be reused in other cells, provided that the same frequencies are not reused in adjacent cells, which would cause co-channel interference.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] This strategy is viable because a given radio frequency can be reused in a different area for an unrelated transmission.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In contrast, a single transmitter can only handle one transmission for a given frequency.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Inevitably, there is some level of interference from the signal from the other cells which use the same frequency.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Consequently, there must be at least one cell gap between cells which reuse the same frequency in a standard frequency-division multiple access (FDMA) system.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Consider the case of a taxi company, where each radio has a manually operated channel selector knob to tune to different frequencies.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] As drivers move around, they change from channel to channel.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The drivers are aware of which frequency approximately covers some area.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] When they do not receive a signal from the transmitter, they try other channels until finding one that works.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The taxi drivers only speak one at a time when invited by the base station operator.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] This is a form of time-division multiple access (TDMA).
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The idea to establish a standard cellular phone network was first proposed on December 11, 1947.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] This proposal was put forward by Douglas H.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Ring, a Bell Labs engineer, in an internal memo suggesting the development of a cellular telephone system by AT&T.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The first commercial cellular network, the 1G generation, was launched in Japan by Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) in 1979, initially in the metropolitan area of Tokyo.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] However, NTT did not initially commercialize the system; the early launch was motivated by an effort to understand a practical cellular system rather than by an interest to profit from it.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In 1981, the Nordic Mobile Telephone system was created as the first network to cover an entire country.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The network was released in 1981 in Sweden and Norway, then in Finland and Denmark in early 1982.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Televerket, a state-owned corporation responsible for telecommunications in Sweden, launched the system.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In September 1981, Jan Stenbeck, a financier and businessman, launched Comvik, a Swedish telecommunications company.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Comvik was the first European telecommunications firm to challenge the state's telephone monopoly on the industry.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] According to sources, Comvik was the first to launch a commercial automatic cellular system before Televerket launched its own in October 1981.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] However, at the time of the new network's release, the Swedish Post and Telecom Authority threatened to shut down the system after claiming that the company had used an unlicensed automatic gear that could interfere with its own networks.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In December 1981, Sweden awarded Comvik with a license to operate its own automatic cellular network in the spirit of market competition.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] First-generation cellular network technology continued to expand its reach to the rest of the world.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In 1990, Millicom Inc., a telecommunications service provider, strategically partnered with Comvik's international cellular operations to become Millicom International Cellular SA.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The company went on to establish a 1G systems foothold in Ghana, Africa under the brand name Mobitel.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In 2006, the company's Ghana operations were renamed to Tigo.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The wireless revolution began in the early 1990s, leading to the transition from analog to digital networks.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The MOSFET invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, was adapted for cellular networks by the early 1990s, with the wide adoption of power MOSFET, LDMOS (RF amplifier), and RF CMOS (RF circuit) devices leading to the development and proliferation of digital wireless mobile networks.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The first commercial digital cellular network, the 2G generation, was launched in 1991.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] This sparked competition in the sector as the new operators challenged the incumbent 1G analog network operators.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] With FDMA, the transmitting and receiving frequencies used by different users in each cell are different from each other.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Each cellular call was assigned a pair of frequencies (one for base to mobile, the other for mobile to base) to provide full-duplex operation.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The original AMPS systems had 666 channel pairs, 333 each for the CLEC "A" system and ILEC "B" system.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The number of channels was expanded to 416 pairs per carrier, but ultimately the number of RF channels limits the number of calls that a cell site could handle.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] FDMA is a familiar technology to telephone companies, which used frequency-division multiplexing to add channels to their point-to-point wireline plants before time-division multiplexing rendered FDM obsolete.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] With TDMA, the transmitting and receiving time slots used by different users in each cell are different from each other.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] TDMA typically uses digital signaling to store and forward bursts of voice data that are fit into time slices for transmission, and expanded at the receiving end to produce a somewhat normal-sounding voice at the receiver.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] TDMA must introduce latency (time delay) into the audio signal.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] As long as the latency time is short enough that the delayed audio is not heard as an echo, it is not problematic.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] TDMA is a familiar technology for telephone companies, which used time-division multiplexing to add channels to their point-to-point wireline plants before packet switching rendered TDM obsolete.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The principle of CDMA is based on spread spectrum technology developed for military use during World War II and improved during the Cold War into direct-sequence spread spectrum that was used for early CDMA cellular systems and Wi-Fi.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] DSSS allows multiple simultaneous phone conversations to take place on a single wideband RF channel, without needing to channelize them in time or frequency.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Although more sophisticated than older multiple access schemes (and unfamiliar to legacy telephone companies because it was not developed by Bell Labs), CDMA has scaled well to become the basis for 3G cellular radio systems.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Other available methods of multiplexing such as MIMO, a more sophisticated version of antenna diversity, combined with active beamforming provides much greater spatial multiplexing ability compared to original AMPS cells, that typically only addressed one to three unique spaces.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Massive MIMO deployment allows much greater channel reuse, thus increasing the number of subscribers per cell site, greater data throughput per user, or some combination thereof.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Quadrature Amplitude Modulation (QAM) modems offer an increasing number of bits per symbol, allowing more users per megahertz of bandwidth (and decibels of SNR), greater data throughput per user, or some combination thereof.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The key characteristic of a cellular network is the ability to reuse frequencies to increase both coverage and capacity.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] As described above, adjacent cells must use different frequencies, however, there is no problem with two cells sufficiently far apart operating on the same frequency, provided the masts and cellular network users' equipment do not transmit with too much power.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The elements that determine frequency reuse are the reuse distance and the reuse factor.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] where *R* is the cell radius and *N* is the number of cells per cluster.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Cells may vary in radius from 1 to 30 kilometres (0.62 to 18.64 mi).
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The boundaries of the cells can also overlap between adjacent cells and large cells can be divided into smaller cells.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The frequency reuse factor is the rate at which the same frequency can be used in the network.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] It is *1/K* (or *K* according to some books) where *K* is the number of cells which cannot use the same frequencies for transmission.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Common values for the frequency reuse factor are 1/3, 1/4, 1/7, 1/9 and 1/12 (or 3, 4, 7, 9 and 12, depending on notation).
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In case of *N* sector antennas on the same base station site, each with different direction, the base station site can serve N different sectors.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] A **reuse pattern** of *N/K* denotes a further division in frequency among *N* sector antennas per site.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Some current and historical reuse patterns are 3/7 (North American AMPS), 6/4 (Motorola NAMPS), and 3/4 (GSM).
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] If the total available bandwidth is *B*, each cell can only use a number of frequency channels corresponding to a bandwidth of *B/K*, and each sector can use a bandwidth of *B/NK*.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Code-division multiple access-based systems use a wider frequency band to achieve the same rate of transmission as FDMA, but this is compensated for by the ability to use a frequency reuse factor of 1, for example using a reuse pattern of 1/1.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In other words, adjacent base station sites use the same frequencies, and the different base stations and users are separated by codes rather than frequencies.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] While *N* is shown as 1 in this example, that does not mean the CDMA cell has only one sector, but rather that the entire cell bandwidth is also available to each sector individually.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Recently also orthogonal frequency-division multiple access based systems such as LTE are being deployed with a frequency reuse of 1.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Since such systems do not spread the signal across the frequency band, inter-cell radio resource management is important to coordinate resource allocation between different cell sites and to limit the inter-cell interference.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] There are various means of inter-cell interference coordination (ICIC) already defined in the standard.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Coordinated scheduling, multi-site MIMO or multi-site beamforming are other examples for inter-cell radio resource management that might be standardized in the future.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Cell towers frequently use a directional signal to improve reception in higher-traffic areas.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In the United States, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) limits omnidirectional cell tower signals to 100 watts of power.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] If the tower has directional antennas, the FCC allows the cell operator to emit up to 500 watts of effective radiated power (ERP).
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Although the original cell towers created an even, omnidirectional signal, were at the centers of the cells and were omnidirectional, a cellular map can be redrawn with the cellular telephone towers located at the corners of the hexagons where three cells converge.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Each tower has three sets of directional antennas aimed in three different directions with 120 degrees for each cell (totaling 360 degrees) and receiving/transmitting into three different cells at different frequencies.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] This provides a minimum of three channels, and three towers for each cell and greatly increases the chances of receiving a usable signal from at least one direction.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The numbers in the illustration are channel numbers, which repeat every 3 cells.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Large cells can be subdivided into smaller cells for high volume areas.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Cell phone companies also use this directional signal to improve reception along highways and inside buildings like stadiums and arenas.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Practically every cellular system has some kind of broadcast mechanism.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] This can be used directly for distributing information to multiple mobiles.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Commonly, for example in mobile telephony systems, the most important use of broadcast information is to set up channels for one-to-one communication between the mobile transceiver and the base station.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The three different paging procedures generally adopted are sequential, parallel and selective paging.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Paging takes place by sending the broadcast message to all of those cells.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Paging messages can be used for information transfer.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] This happens in pagers, in CDMA systems for sending SMS messages, and in the UMTS system where it allows for low downlink latency in packet-based connections.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In LTE/4G, the Paging procedure is initiated by the MME when data packets need to be delivered to the UE.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In a primitive taxi system, when the taxi moved away from a first tower and closer to a second tower, the taxi driver manually switched from one frequency to another as needed.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] If communication was interrupted due to a loss of a signal, the taxi driver asked the base station operator to repeat the message on a different frequency.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In a cellular system, as the distributed mobile transceivers move from cell to cell during an ongoing continuous communication, switching from one cell frequency to a different cell frequency is done electronically without interruption and without a base station operator or manual switching.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Typically, a new channel is automatically selected for the mobile unit on the new base station which will serve it.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The mobile unit then automatically switches from the current channel to the new channel and communication continues.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The exact details of the mobile system's move from one base station to the other vary considerably from system to system (see the example below for how a mobile phone network manages handover).
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The most common example of a cellular network is a mobile phone (cell phone) network.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] A mobile phone is a portable telephone which receives or makes calls through a cell site (base station) or transmitting tower.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Radio waves are used to transfer signals to and from the cell phone.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Modern mobile phone networks use cells because radio frequencies are a limited, shared resource.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Cell-sites and handsets change frequency under computer control and use low power transmitters so that the usually limited number of radio frequencies can be simultaneously used by many callers with less interference.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] A cellular network is used by the mobile phone operator to achieve both coverage and capacity for their subscribers.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Large geographic areas are split into smaller cells to avoid line-of-sight signal loss and to support a large number of active phones in that area.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] All of the cell sites are connected to telephone exchanges (or switches), which in turn connect to the public telephone network.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In cities, each cell site may have a range of up to approximately 1⁄2 mile (0.80 km), while in rural areas, the range could be as much as 5 miles (8.0 km).
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] It is possible that in clear open areas, a user may receive signals from a cell site 25 miles (40 km) away.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In rural areas with low-band coverage and tall towers, basic voice and messaging service may reach 50 miles (80 km), with limitations on bandwidth and number of simultaneous calls.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Since almost all mobile phones use cellular technology, including GSM, CDMA, and AMPS (analog), the term "cell phone" is in some regions, notably the US, used interchangeably with "mobile phone".
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] However, satellite phones are mobile phones that do not communicate directly with a ground-based cellular tower but may do so indirectly by way of a satellite.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The transition from existing analog to the digital standard followed a very different path in Europe and the US.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] As a consequence, multiple digital standards surfaced in the US, while Europe and many countries converged towards the GSM standard.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] This network is the foundation of the GSM system network.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] There are many functions that are performed by this network in order to make sure customers get the desired service including mobility management, registration, call set-up, and handover.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Any phone connects to the network via an RBS (Radio Base Station) at a corner of the corresponding cell which in turn connects to the Mobile switching center (MSC).
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The MSC provides a connection to the public switched telephone network (PSTN).
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The link from a phone to the RBS is called an *uplink* while the other way is termed *downlink*.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Radio channels effectively use the transmission medium through the use of the following multiplexing and access schemes: frequency-division multiple access (FDMA), time-division multiple access (TDMA), code-division multiple access (CDMA), and space-division multiple access (SDMA).
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] As the phone user moves from one cell area to another cell while a call is in progress, the mobile station will search for a new channel to attach to in order not to drop the call.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Once a new channel is found, the network will command the mobile unit to switch to the new channel and at the same time switch the call onto the new channel.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] With CDMA, multiple CDMA handsets share a specific radio channel.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The signals are separated by using a pseudonoise code (PN code) that is specific to each phone.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] As the user moves from one cell to another, the handset sets up radio links with multiple cell sites (or sectors of the same site) simultaneously.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] This is known as "soft handoff" because, unlike with traditional cellular technology, there is no one defined point where the phone switches to the new cell.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In IS-95 inter-frequency handovers and older analog systems such as NMT it will typically be impossible to test the target channel directly while communicating.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In this case, other techniques have to be used such as pilot beacons in IS-95.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] This means that there is almost always a brief break in the communication while searching for the new channel followed by the risk of an unexpected return to the old channel.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] If there is no ongoing communication or the communication can be interrupted, it is possible for the mobile unit to spontaneously move from one cell to another and then notify the base station with the strongest signal.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The effect of frequency on cell coverage means that different frequencies serve better for different uses.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Low frequencies, such as 450 MHz NMT, serve very well for countryside coverage.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] GSM 900 (900 MHz) is suitable for light urban coverage.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] GSM 1800 (1.8 GHz) starts to be limited by structural walls.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] UMTS, at 2.1 GHz is quite similar in coverage to GSM 1800.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Higher frequencies are a disadvantage when it comes to coverage, but it is a decided advantage when it comes to capacity.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Picocells, covering e.g. one floor of a building, become possible, and the same frequency can be used for cells which are practically neighbors.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] Cell service area may also vary due to interference from transmitting systems, both within and around that cell.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] This is true especially in CDMA based systems.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] The receiver requires a certain signal-to-noise ratio, and the transmitter should not send with too high transmission power in view to not cause interference with other transmitters.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] As the receiver moves away from the transmitter, the power received decreases, so the power control algorithm of the transmitter increases the power it transmits to restore the level of received power.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] As the interference (noise) rises above the received power from the transmitter, and the power of the transmitter cannot be increased anymore, the signal becomes corrupted and eventually unusable.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In CDMA-based systems, the effect of interference from other mobile transmitters in the same cell on coverage area is very marked and has a special name, *cell breathing*.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] One can see examples of cell coverage by studying some of the coverage maps provided by real operators on their web sites or by looking at independently crowdsourced maps such as Opensignal or CellMapper.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] In certain cases they may mark the site of the transmitter; in others, it can be calculated by working out the point of strongest coverage.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] A cellular repeater is used to extend cell coverage into larger areas.
[src:cellular-6g/cellular-network] They range from wideband repeaters for consumer use in homes and offices to smart or digital repeaters for industrial needs.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Optical communications, in various forms, have been used for thousands of years.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The ancient Greeks used a coded alphabetic system of signalling with torches developed by Cleoxenus, Democleitus and Polybius.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] In the modern era, semaphores and wireless solar telegraphs called heliographs were developed, using coded signals to communicate with their recipients.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] In 1880, Alexander Graham Bell and his assistant Charles Sumner Tainter created the photophone, at Bell's newly established Volta Laboratory in Washington, DC.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Bell considered it his most important invention.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The device allowed for the transmission of sound on a beam of light.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] On June 3, 1880, Bell conducted the world's first wireless telephone transmission between two buildings, some 213 meters (699 feet) apart.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Its first practical use came in military communication systems many decades later, first for optical telegraphy.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] German colonial troops used heliograph telegraphy transmitters during the Herero Wars starting in 1904, in German South-West Africa (today's Namibia) as did British, French, US or Ottoman signals.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Optical telephone communications were tested at the end of the war, but not introduced at troop level.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] In addition, special blinkgeräts were used for communication with airplanes, balloons, and tanks, with varying success.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] A major technological step was to replace the Morse code by modulating optical waves in speech transmission.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Carl Zeiss, Jena developed the **Lichtsprechgerät* 80/80* (literal translation: optical speaking device) that the German army used in their World War II anti-aircraft defense units, or in bunkers at the Atlantic Wall.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The invention of lasers in the 1960s revolutionized free-space optics.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Military organizations were particularly interested and boosted their development.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] However, laser-based free-space optics lost market momentum when the installation of optical fiber networks for civilian uses was at its peak.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Many simple and inexpensive consumer remote controls use low-speed communication using infrared (IR) light.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] This is known as consumer IR technologies.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Free-space point-to-point optical links can be implemented using infrared laser light, although low-data-rate communication over short distances is possible using LEDs.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Infrared Data Association (IrDA) technology is a very simple form of free-space optical communications.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] On the communications side the FSO technology is considered as a part of the optical wireless communications applications.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Free-space optics can be used for communications between spacecraft.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The reliability of FSO units has always been a problem for commercial telecommunications.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Consistently, studies find too many dropped packets and signal errors over small ranges (400 to 500 meters (1,300 to 1,600 ft)).
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] This is from both independent studies, such as in the Czech Republic, as well as internal studies, such as one conducted by MRV FSO staff.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Military based studies consistently produce longer estimates for reliability, projecting the maximum range for terrestrial links is of the order of 2 to 3 km (1.2 to 1.9 mi).
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] All studies agree the stability and quality of the link is highly dependent on atmospheric factors such as rain, fog, dust and heat.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Relays may be employed to extend the range for FSO communications.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] TMEX USA ran two eight-mile links between Laredo, Texas and Nuevo Laredo, Mexico from 1998 to 2002.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The links operated at 155 Mbit/s and reliably carried phone calls and internet service.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The main reason terrestrial communications have been limited to non-commercial telecommunications functions is fog.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Fog often prevents FSO laser links over 500 meters (1,600 ft) from achieving a year-round availability sufficient for commercial services.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Several entities are continually attempting to overcome these key disadvantages to FSO communications and field a system with a better quality of service.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] DARPA has sponsored over US$130 million in research toward this effort, with the ORCA and ORCLE programs.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Other non-government groups are fielding tests to evaluate different technologies that some claim have the ability to address key FSO adoption challenges.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] As of October 2014, none have fielded a working system that addresses the most common atmospheric events.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] FSO research from 1998 to 2006 in the private sector totaled $407.1 million, divided primarily among four start-up companies.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] One private company published a paper on November 20, 2014, claiming they had achieved commercial reliability (99.999% availability) in extreme fog.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] There is no indication this product is currently commercially available.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The massive advantages of laser communication in space have multiple space agencies racing to develop a stable space communication platform, with many significant demonstrations and achievements.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The first gigabit laser-based communication was achieved by the European Space Agency and called the European Data Relay System (EDRS) on November 28, 2014.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The system is operational and is being used on a daily basis.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] In December 2023, the Australian National University (ANU) demonstrated its Quantum Optical Ground Station at its Mount Stromlo Observatory.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] QOGS uses adaptive optics and lasers as part of a telescope, to create a bi-directional communications system capable of supporting the NASA Artemis program to the Moon.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] A two-way distance record for communication was set by the Mercury laser altimeter instrument aboard the *MESSENGER* spacecraft.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] It was able to communicate across a distance of 24 million km (15 million mi), as the craft neared Earth on a fly-by in May 2005.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The previous record had been set with a one-way detection of laser light from Earth by the Galileo probe, of 6 million km (3.7 million mi) in 1992.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] In January 2013, NASA used lasers to beam an image of the Mona Lisa to the Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter roughly 390,000 km (240,000 mi) away.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] To compensate for atmospheric interference, an error correction code algorithm similar to that used in CDs was implemented.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] In the early morning hours of October 18, 2013, NASA's Lunar Laser Communication Demonstration (LLCD) transmitted data from lunar orbit to Earth at a rate of 622 megabits per second (Mbit/s).
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] LLCD was flown aboard the Lunar Atmosphere and Dust Environment Explorer (LADEE) spacecraft, whose primary science mission was to investigate the tenuous and exotic atmosphere that exists around the Moon.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Between April and July 2014 NASA's OPALS instrument successfully uploaded 175 megabytes in 3.5 seconds and downloaded 200–300 MB in 20 s.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Their system was also able to re-acquire tracking after the signal was lost due to cloud cover.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] On December 7, 2021 NASA launched the Laser Communications Relay Demonstration (LCRD), which aims to relay data between spacecraft in geosynchronous orbit and ground stations.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] LCRD is NASA's first two-way, end-to-end optical relay.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] LCRD uses two ground stations, Optical Ground Station (OGS)-1 and -2, at Table Mountain Observatory in California, and Haleakalā, Hawaii.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] One of LCRD's first operational users is the Integrated LCRD Low-Earth Orbit User Modem and Amplifier Terminal (ILLUMA-T), on the International Space Station.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The terminal will receive high-resolution science data from experiments and instruments on board the space station and then transfer this data to LCRD, which will then transmit it to a ground station.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] After the data arrives on Earth, it will be delivered to mission operation centers and mission scientists.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The ILLUMA-T payload was sent to the ISS in late 2023 on SpaceX CRS-29, and achieved first light on December 5, 2023.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] On April 28, 2023, NASA and its partners achieved 200 gigabit per second (Gbit/s) throughput on a space-to-ground optical link between a satellite in orbit and Earth.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] This was achieved by the TeraByte InfraRed Delivery (TBIRD) system, mounted on NASA's Pathfinder Technology Demonstrator 3 (PTD-3) satellite.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Various satellite constellations that are intended to provide global broadband coverage, such as SpaceX Starlink, employ laser communication for inter-satellite links.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] This effectively creates a space-based optical mesh network between the satellites.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] In 2001, Twibright Labs released RONJA Metropolis, an open-source DIY 10 Mbit/s full-duplex LED FSO system that can span 1.4 km (0.87 mi).
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] In 2004, a visible light communication consortium was formed in Japan.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] This was based on work from researchers that used a white LED-based space lighting system for indoor local area network (LAN) communications.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] These systems present advantages over traditional UHF RF-based systems from improved isolation between systems, the size and cost of receivers/transmitters, RF licensing laws and by combining space lighting and communication into the same system.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] In January 2009, a task force for visible light communication was formed by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers working group for wireless personal area network standards known as IEEE 802.15.7.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Amateur radio operators have achieved significantly farther distances using incoherent sources of light from high-intensity LEDs.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] However, physical limitations of the equipment used limited bandwidths to about 4 kHz.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The high sensitivities required of the detector to cover such distances made the internal capacitance of the photodiode used a dominant factor in the high-impedance amplifier which followed it, thus naturally forming a low-pass filter with a cut-off frequency in the 4 kHz range.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Lasers can reach very high data rates which are comparable to fiber communications.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Projected data rates and future data rate claims vary.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] A low-cost white LED (GaN-phosphor) which could be used for space lighting can typically be modulated up to 20 MHz.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Data rates of over 100 Mbit/s can be achieved using efficient modulation schemes and Siemens claimed to have achieved over 500 Mbit/s in 2010.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Research published in 2009, used a similar system for traffic control of automated vehicles with LED traffic lights.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] In September 2013, pureLiFi, the Edinburgh start-up working on Li-Fi, also demonstrated high speed point-to-point connectivity using any off-the-shelf LED light bulb.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] In previous work, high bandwidth specialist LEDs have been used to achieve the high data rates.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The new system, the Li-1st, maximizes the available optical bandwidth for any LED device, thereby reducing the cost and improving the performance of deploying indoor FSO systems.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] The light beam can be very narrow, which makes FSO hard to intercept, improving security.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Encryption can secure the data traversing the link.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] FSO provides vastly improved electromagnetic interference (EMI) behavior compared to using microwaves.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] These factors cause an attenuated receiver signal and lead to higher bit error ratio (BER).
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] To overcome these issues, vendors found some solutions, like multi-beam or multi-path architectures, which use more than one sender and more than one receiver.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Some state-of-the-art devices also have larger fade margin (extra power, reserved for rain, smog, fog).
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] To keep an eye-safe environment, good FSO systems have a limited laser power density and support laser classes 1 or 1M.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Atmospheric and fog attenuation, which are exponential in nature, limit practical range of FSO devices to several kilometers.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] However, free-space optics based on 1550 nm wavelength, have considerably lower optical loss than free-space optics using 830 nm wavelength, in dense fog conditions.
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] FSO using wavelength 1550 nm system are capable of transmitting several times higher power than systems with 850 nm and are safe to the human eye (1M class).
[src:cellular-6g/free-space-optical-communication] Additionally, some free-space optics, such as EC SYSTEM, ensure higher connection reliability in bad weather conditions by constantly monitoring link quality to regulate laser diode transmission power with built-in automatic gain control.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] For this reason, this technology assumes a central role to support 5G mobile networks that are designed to efficiently embrace a plethora of services with very different service level requirements (SLR).
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The realization of this service-oriented view of the network leverages on the concepts of software-defined networking (SDN) and network function virtualization (NFV) that allow the implementation of flexible and scalable network slices on top of a common network infrastructure.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] From a business model perspective, each network slice is administrated by a mobile virtual network operator (MVNO).
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The infrastructure provider (the owner of the telecommunication infrastructure) leases its physical resources to the MVNOs that share the underlying physical network.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] According to the availability of the assigned resources, a MVNO can autonomously deploy multiple network slices that are customized to the various applications provided to its own users.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The history of network slicing can be tracked back to the late 1980s with the introduction of the concept of "slice" in the networking field.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Overlay networks provided the first form of network slicing since heterogeneous network resources were combined to create virtual networks over a common infrastructure.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] However, they lacked a mechanism that could enable their programmability.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] In the early 2000s, PlanetLab introduced a virtualization framework that allowed groups of users to program network functions in order to obtain isolated and application-specific slices.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The advent of SDN technologies in 2009 further extended the programmability capabilities via open interfaces that enabled the realization of fully configurable and scalable network slices.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] In the context of mobile networks, network slicing evolved from the concept of RAN sharing that was initially introduced in the LTE standard.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Examples of such technology are multi-operator radio access networks (MORAN) and multi-operator core networks (MOCN), which allow network operators to share common LTE resources within the same radio access network (RAN).
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Network slicing emerges as an essential technique in 5G networks to accommodate such different and possibly contrasting quality of service (QoS) requirements exploiting a single physical network infrastructure.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The basic idea of network slicing is to "slice" the original network architecture in multiple logical and independent networks that are configured to effectively meet the various services requirements.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] In commercial terms, network slicing allows a mobile operator to create specific virtual networks that cater to particular clients and use cases.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Certain applications - such as mobile broadband, machine-to-machine communications (e.g. in manufacturing or logistics), or smart cars - will benefit from leveraging different aspects of 5G technology.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] One might require higher speeds, another low latency, and yet another access to edge computing resources.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] By creating separate slices that prioritise specific resources a 5G operator can offer tailored solutions to particular industries.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Some sources insist this will revolutionise industries like marketing, augmented reality, or mobile gaming, while others are more cautious, pointing to unevenness in network coverage and poor reach of advantages beyond increased speed.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Slicing will be very useful to MVNOs as different use cases can be supported in a layer based on parameters like low latency high speed for video streaming for OTT focused MVNOs, similarly telemetry operations could have lower speed parameter and as on.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Although there are different proposals of network slice architectures, it is possible to define a general architecture that maps the common elements of each solution into a general and unified framework.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] From a high-level perspective, the network slicing architecture can be considered as composed of two mains blocks, one dedicated to the actual slice implementation and the other dedicated to the slice management and configuration.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The first block is designed as a multi-tier architecture composed by three layers (service layer, network function layer, infrastructure layer), where each one contributes to the slice definition and deployment with distinct tasks.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The second block is designed as a centralized network entity, generically denoted as *network slice controller*, that monitors and manages the functionalities between the three layers in order to efficiently coordinate the coexistence of multiple slices.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The service layer interfaces directly with the network business entities (e.g.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] MVNOs and 3rd party service providers) that share the underlying physical network and it provides a unified vision of the service requirements.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Each service is formally represented as *service instance*, which embeds all the network characteristics in the form of SLA requirements that are expected to be fully satisfied by a suitable slice creation.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The network function layer is in charge of the creation of each network slice according to service instance requests coming from the upper layer.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] It is composed of a set of *network functions* that embody well-defined behaviors and interfaces.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Multiple network functions are placed over the virtual network infrastructure and chained together to create an end-to-end network slice instance that reflects the network characteristics requested by the service.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The configuration of the network functions are performed by means of a set of *network operations* that allow management of their full lifecycle (from their placement when a slice is created to their de-allocation when the function provided is no longer needed).
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] To increase resource usage efficiency, the same network function can be simultaneously shared by different slices at the cost of an increase in the complexity of operations management.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Conversely, a one-to-one mapping between each network function and each slice eases the configuration procedures, but can lead to poor and inefficient resource usage.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The infrastructure layer represents the actual physical network topology (radio access network, transport network and core network) upon which every network slice is multiplexed and it provides the physical network resources to host the several network functions composing each slice.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The network domain of the available resources includes a heterogeneous set of infrastructure components like data centers (storage and computation capacity resources), devices enabling network connectivity such as routers (networking resources) and base stations (radio bandwidth resources).
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The network slice controller is defined as a network orchestrator, which interfaces with the various functionalities performed by each layer to coherently manage each slice request.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The benefit of such network element is that it enables an efficient and flexible slice creation that can be reconfigured during its life-cycle.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Due to the complexity of the performed tasks which address different purposes, the network slice controller can be composed by multiple orchestrators that independently manage a subset of functionalities of each layer.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] To fulfill the service requirements, the various orchestration entities need to coordinate with each other by exchanging high-level information about the state of the operations involved in the slice creation and deployment.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Slice isolation is an important requirement that allows enforcing the core concept of network slicing about the simultaneous coexistence of multiple slices sharing the same infrastructure.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] This property is achieved by imposing that each slice's performance must not have any impact on the other slice's performance.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Slicing has become an important part of 5G networks, but it doesn't have to forget to guarantee the QoS.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Some studies have demonstrated that formulating the problem with the QoS as a stochastic problem, permit us to maximize the average throughput of the AP, while satisfying the constraints related to the QoS.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Monetizing 5G services faster is one of the topics that interests network operators the most because the costs of building and maintaining 5G networks are high, and it's difficult to predict the demand for 5G services.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] 5G network slicing is one of the effective ways to offer customized services for different industries such as manufacturing, transportation, and healthcare.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Combined with AIOps, ML/AI-driven automation and 5G lifecycle optimization, it can reduce OpEx and increase revenues for network operators.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] In the 3GPP 5G core architecture, the user plane and control plane functions are separated.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Control plane capabilities, for instance, session management, access authentication, policy management, and user data storage are independent of the user plane functionality.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The user plane handles packet forwarding, encapsulation or de-capsulation, and associated transport level specifics.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] This separation leads to the distribution of the user plane functions close to the edge of network slices (e.g., so as to reduce latency) and to be independent of the control plane.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The AMF (as a function of the CP) controls UEs that have been authenticated to use the services of the operator and manages the mobility of the UEs across the gNBs.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The SMF (again part of the CP) manages the sessions of UEs, while AMF transmits the session management messages between the UEs and SMF.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] UPF (as part of the UP) performs the processing and forwarding of the user data.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] NSSF (as a function of the CP) is responsible for the management and orchestration of network slices.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] CSMF (as a function of the CP) translates the requirements of services to requirements relating to network slices.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] 5G Core network functions can be sliced to support specific services for different UEs.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Thanks to the modular nature of the 5G core, the network functions of the 5G core can be split and shared between different network slices to reduce management complexity.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] In general, we can perform 5G core network slicing in two ways.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] We can implement dedicated core network functions per network slice.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] In this architecture, each network slice has a set of completely dedicated core network functions (e.g., AUSF, AMF, SMF, and UDM).
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The UEs can access various services from network slices and different core networks.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Alternatively, we can share some control plane functions between the network slices while others such as user plane functions are slice specific (e.g., UPF).
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] AMF is usually shared by several network slices, while SMF and UPF are usually dedicated to specific network slices.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The AMF function will be shared between different network slices in order to reduce the mobility management signaling when the UE uses the services of different network slices simultaneously.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] For example, UE location management or the control signaling between the UE and the old AMF will be reduced when it will be connected to the new AMF of another network slice.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Also, UDM and NSSF are typically shared by all network slices to reduce the management complexity of network slices.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] The emergence of network slicing also exposes novel security and privacy challenges, primarily related to aspects such as network slicing life-cycle security, inter-slice security, intra-slice security, slice broker security, zero-touch network and management security, and blockchain security.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Therefore, enhancing the security, privacy, and trust of network slicing has become a key research area toward realizing the true capabilities of 5G.
[src:cellular-6g/network-slicing] Various security solutions are proposed for resolving the security threats, challenges, and issues of network slicing.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] Wavelengths of radiation in the decimillimeter band correspondingly range 1 mm to 0.1 mm = 100 μm and those in the terahertz band 3 mm = 3000 μm to 30 μm.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] Because terahertz radiation begins at a wavelength of around 1 millimeter and proceeds into shorter wavelengths, it is sometimes known as the *submillimeter band*, and its radiation as *submillimeter waves*, especially in astronomy.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] This band of electromagnetic radiation lies within the transition region between microwave and far infrared and can be regarded as either.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] Compared to lower radio frequencies, terahertz radiation is strongly absorbed by the gases of the atmosphere, and in air, most of the energy is attenuated within a few meters, so it is not practical for long distance terrestrial radio communication.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] It can penetrate thin layers of materials but is blocked by thicker objects.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] THz beams transmitted through materials can be used for material characterization, layer inspection, relief measurement, and as a lower-energy alternative to X-rays for producing high resolution images of the interior of solid objects.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] Terahertz radiation occupies a middle ground where the ranges of microwaves and infrared light waves overlap, known as the "terahertz gap"; it is called a "gap" because the technology for its generation and manipulation is still in its infancy.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] The generation and modulation of electromagnetic waves in this frequency range ceases to be possible by the conventional electronic devices used to generate radio waves and microwaves, requiring the development of new devices and techniques.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] Terahertz radiation falls in between infrared radiation and microwave radiation in the electromagnetic spectrum, and it shares some properties with each of these.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] Terahertz radiation travels in a line of sight and is non-ionizing.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] Like microwaves, terahertz radiation can penetrate a wide variety of non-conducting materials; clothing, paper, cardboard, wood, masonry, plastic and ceramics.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] The penetration depth is typically less than that of microwave radiation.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] Like infrared, terahertz radiation has limited penetration through fog and clouds and cannot penetrate liquid water or metal.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] Terahertz radiation can penetrate some distance through body tissue like x-rays, but unlike them is non-ionizing, so it is of interest as a replacement for medical X-rays.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] Due to its longer wavelength, images made using terahertz waves have lower resolution than X-rays and need to be enhanced (see figure at right).
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] The earth's atmosphere is a strong absorber of terahertz radiation, so the range of terahertz radiation in air is limited to tens of meters, making it unsuitable for long-distance communications.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] However, at distances of ~10 meters the band may still allow many useful applications in imaging and construction of high bandwidth wireless networking systems, especially indoor systems.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] In addition, producing and detecting coherent terahertz radiation remains technically challenging, though inexpensive commercial sources now exist in the 0.3–1.0 THz range (the lower part of the spectrum), including gyrotrons, backward wave oscillators, and resonant-tunneling diodes.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] Due to the small energy of THz photons, current THz devices require low temperature during operation to suppress environmental noise.
[src:cellular-6g/terahertz-radiation] Tremendous efforts thus have been put into THz research to improve the operation temperature, using different strategies such as optomechanical meta-devices.
